\noindent\textbf{Rebuttal.}
We thank the reviewers for their constructive feedback. All reviewers recognize the motivation and practicality of \method{}: extending multimodal long-context by \emph{token-dimension} (KV width) compression rather than reducing token count. Below we address the main concerns: (i) novelty/positioning w.r.t.\ prior MLA, (ii) calibration robustness/reproducibility, (iii) potential loss of fine-grained spatiotemporal cues, and (iv) end-to-end efficiency and recovery training.

\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{Novelty beyond prior MLA / ``incremental'' concern (R1,R3).}
We agree that latent/factorized attention has strong prior art in text-only LLMs. Our contribution is a \emph{general and multimodal-ready conversion framework} that re-parameterizes mainstream pretrained MLLM attention blocks (MHA/MQA/GQA and common variants) into RoPE-consistent latent KV attention \emph{as a drop-in upgrade}, plus multimodal components needed to avoid information migration.
(1) \textbf{Architecture robustness:} existing TransMLA-style conversions are sensitive to block details; our procedure handles architectural deviations (e.g., QK-Norm inside GQA). We successfully convert \emph{Qwen3-VL} and obtain \textbf{69.74} on VideoMME vs.\ baseline \textbf{68.89} (Table~X).
(2) \textbf{Multimodal specificity:} even if a language backbone uses MLA, the vision side (e.g., ViT) still relies on standard attention; we extend conversion to multimodal modules while preserving positional structure via RoPE-aware aggregation. \textbf{Modality-Aware Adapters} + \textbf{Visual Latent Budgeting} are introduced to preserve compact multimodal features and achieve better perf--memory tradeoffs. We will revise the related-work section to more explicitly delineate these contributions from prior MLA papers.

\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{Does token-dimension compression harm fine-grained cues? (R1,R3).}
We directly test fine-grained temporal/spatial perception and do not observe the claimed degradation:
\emph{(i) Temporal grounding:} on Charades-STA (Table~2), \method{} \textbf{improves} temporal precision (R@0.5 \textbf{+5.3\%}, mIoU \textbf{+3.7\%}), suggesting latent compression mainly removes redundancy and can sharpen boundaries.
\emph{(ii) Fine-grained perception:} on MVBench, \method{} essentially matches baseline (\textbf{74.3} vs.\ \textbf{74.4}).
\emph{(iii) Extreme long context:} Needle-in-a-Haystack retains \textbf{94.2\%} accuracy (Supp.\ Fig.~X).
We will add a latent-dimension sweep (new Table/Fig.~X) to explicitly show the failure boundary when compression becomes overly aggressive.

\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{Calibration robustness and reproducibility (R1).}
Calibration is not intended to learn new capabilities; it estimates stable dominant structure (principal directions) for RoPE-aware aggregation and low-rank projections. Empirically, it is largely insensitive to calibration data choice. All main results use only \textbf{$\sim$128k} text tokens from \textbf{WikiText2} with \textbf{X} calibration steps, updating only the LLM. We have additional ablations (new Table~X) varying calibration scale/modality that show only marginal differences. We will add full details (dataset composition, scale, steps, hyperparameters) in the revision.

\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{End-to-end efficiency: latency/FLOPs and adapter overhead (R2).}
We agree latency should be reported. KV-cache is reduced by $\sim$2$\times$ (Table~1), which reduces memory traffic; long-context decoding is typically memory-bandwidth dominated, so this yields practical throughput gains. Measured decode throughput (same hardware/settings; to be fully specified in revision):
\begin{center}
\vspace{-0.4em}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Model & Prefill & Decode (tok/s) \\
\midrule
\method{} & 32k & 52.47 \\
\method{} & 64k & 47.24 \\
Original & 32k & 32.41 \\
Original & 64k & 25.88 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\vspace{-0.6em}
\end{center}
The added modality adapters are lightweight linear layers; their compute is negligible compared to attention at long sequence lengths (details/FLOPs breakdown will be added).

\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{Recovery training amount (R2).}
We ran a lightweight recovery study (8$\times$A100, effective batch size 16, 15k steps). Baseline on VideoMME is 63\%; after migration, 200-step alignment already reaches 57\% (90.5\% of baseline), 700 steps: 58.6\% (93\%), 3k: 60.5\% (94.1\%), and $\sim$8k reaches the reported best. This indicates recovery is not brittle and most performance is restored quickly.

\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{Orthogonality to token reduction (R2,R3).}
Our experiments already combine both: the base model VideoChat-Flash performs token reduction (e.g., 16 tokens/frame). Table~2 compares token-reduction-only vs.\ token-reduction+\method{}; adding token-dimension compression preserves performance (e.g., MVBench 63.5 vs.\ 63.3) while reducing KV width by $\sim$50\% (1024$\rightarrow$530). Thus token count reduction shrinks $T$, while our method shrinks per-token KV width; they are complementary.

\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{Minor fixes.}
We will fix the incomplete Fig.~1 caption and add missing calibration/throughput measurement details for full reproducibility.
```

