We thank the reviewers for their feedback. All reviewers recognize the motivation and practicality of our method: extending multimodal long-context by \emph{token-dimension} compression rather than reducing token count. Below we address the main concerns: (i) novelty w.r.t.\ prior MLA, (ii) orthogonality to token reduction, (iii) potential loss of fine-grained visual cues, (iv) calibration robustness, and (v) end-to-end efficiency and recovery training.
\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{(i) Novelty beyond prior MLA (R1 YciJ, R3 kqV4).}
We agree latent/factorized attention is well-studied in text-only LLMs. We contribute a \emph{general, multimodal-ready conversion} that turns pretrained MLLM attention (MHA/MQA/GQA and variants) into RoPE-consistent latent-KV attention \emph{as a drop-in upgrade}, plus multimodal modules to prevent information migration.
(1) \textbf{Architecture robustness:} MLA-style conversions are block-sensitive; ours handles deviations (e.g., QK-Norm in GQA). We convert \emph{Qwen3-VL} and reach \textbf{69.74} on VideoMME vs.\ \textbf{68.89} baseline.
(2) \textbf{Multimodal specificity:} text-based MLA ignores the \textbf{distribution shift} between visual/text tokens; forcing both into one low-rank latent space often degrades. We add \textbf{Modality-Aware Adapters} and \textbf{Visual Latent Budgeting} to compress vision while preserving later, higher-density text tokens and reserving extra storage for larger head dimensions. We will revise related work to better separate these from prior MLA.
\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{(ii) Orthogonality to token reduction (R2 THCN, R3 kqV4).}
Our experiments have \textbf{already} combined both: the base model VideoChat-Flash performs token reduction (e.g., 16 tokens/frame). Table~2 compares token-reduction-only vs.\ token-reduction+M$^2$LA; adding token-dimension compression preserves performance (e.g., VideoMME 63.5 vs.\ 63.3) while reducing KV width by $\sim$50\% (1024$\rightarrow$530). Thus token count reduction shrinks $T$, while our method shrinks per-token KV width; they are complementary. Empirically, we see no negative interaction in Table 2.
\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{(iii) Effect on fine-grained cues (R1 YciJ, R3 kqV4).}
We test fine-grained temporal/spatial perception (Table 2 in Sec. 4.2) and see no degradation:
\emph{(i) Temporal grounding:} on Charades-STA, M$^2$LA \textbf{improves} precision (R@0.5 \textbf{+5.3\%}, mIoU \textbf{+3.7\%}), indicating compression mainly removes redundancy.
\emph{(ii) Fine-grained perception:} on MVBench, M$^2$LA outperforms baseline (\textbf{74.3} vs.\ \textbf{73.4}).
\emph{(iii) Extreme long context:} Needle-in-a-Haystack retains \textbf{94.2\%} accuracy (Supp.\ Fig.1).
\noindent\textbf{Failure Boundary Analysis (R1 YciJ).} We sweep latent dimensions on \textbf{Qwen3-VL} (Table~\ref{tab:sweep}) and find strong robustness: at 50\% retention, VideoMME even \textbf{improves} (\textbf{69.74} vs.\ 68.89); at 31\% retention it remains strong (VideoMME \textbf{68.11}, PPL 14.47 vs.\ 11.31). Noticeable degradation emerges only when retention drops to \textbf{0.19} (PPL spikes to \textbf{32.9+}), indicating the failure boundary is around 20\% and our default setting stays in a safe zone.
