\vspace{0.2em}\noindent\textbf{(v) End-to-end efficiency: latency/FLOPs and adapter overhead (R2 THCN).}
We report latency. The KV-cache of M$^2$LA is reduced by $\sim$2$\times$ (Table~1), which alleviates the heavy memory I/O that becomes the performance bottleneck in long-context scenarios; this yields practical throughput gains while simultaneously expanding capacity.
Throughput is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:throughput_comparison}, measured on a single NVIDIA H200 GPU with batch size 1 using greedy decoding under bf16 precision with FlashAttention enabled; each point is averaged over 10 runs after warm-up.
The added modality adapters are lightweight linear layers; their compute is negligible compared to attention at long sequence lengths (details/FLOPs breakdown will be added). We've fixed the incomplete caption.
